{{Communism sidebar}} The '''Jam Saqi trial''' (or '''Jam Saqi case'''), was a political and judicial program in the [[History of Pakistan|history]] of Pakistan marked by a rise of widespread fear of expansion of [[Soviet communism|communism]] and the [[Socialism in Pakistan|socialism]].<ref name="Cambridge University Press">{{cite book|last=Newberg|first=Paula R.|title=Judging the state : courts and constitutional politics in Pakistan|year=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=0521894409|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PbSeGQO3xdsC&pg=PA152 |edition=1st paperback}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Eickelman|first=ed. by Dale F.|title=Russia's Muslim frontiers : new directions in cross-cultural analysis|year=1993|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=0253208238}}</ref> There were series of federal investigations led by the [[Federal Investigation Agency|FIA]] and federal prosecution trials conducted by the specialized [[Judge Advocate General Branch (Pakistan)|military courts]] in which the leaders of the [[Pakistan Communist Party|communist]] and [[Pakistan Peoples Party|socialist]] parties were accused of plotting to overthrow the [[Zia regime|military government]] in order to install a [[Movement for the Restoration of Democracy|socialist system]].<ref name="The Himal">{{cite web|last=Mujtaba|first=Hasan|title=This believer was a communist|url=http://www.himalmag.com/component/content/article/2331-This-believer-was-a-communist.html|work=1999 Publications|publisher=''The Himal''|accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref>
During this period, thousands of Pakistani political workers and dissidents were accused of being communists, and hatching a plot against the [[Operation Fair Play|martial law]] which was in effect since 1977. The first trial implicated in 1980 and all trials were conducted at the special sessions held at the [[Karachi Central Jail]].<ref name="Pakistan Association for Mental Health">{{cite book|last=Nomani|first=Javed|title=Behind bars|year=1993|publisher=Pakistan Association for Mental Health|location=Karachi, Pakistan|isbn=9698224009}}</ref> Primarily, the leaders of the [[Pakistan Communist Party|communist party]] were convicted whilst [[Pakistan Peoples Party|socialists]] were acquitted from the trial in the mid 1980s.<ref name="The Marxist">{{cite news|title=Interview with Jam Saqi|url=http://www.marxist.com/veteran-pakistan-communist-jam-saqi040407.htm|accessdate=22 November 2013|newspaper=The Marxist|date=3 April 2007|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
==Origins==
===Communism and struggle=== {{Main|Rawalpindi Conspiracy case|Peshawar Conspiracy Cases}}
The historical judicial period that has come to be known as "Jam Saqi case" began well before the trial was launched in the 1980s. Many factors contributed to this inquiry, some of them extending back to the year 1950 with the [[Rawalpindi Conspiracy case|first case]], further amplified by [[Communism in Pakistan|Communism]]'s emergence as a recognized [[Politics of Pakistan|political force]]. After the [[Pakistani general elections, 1977|general elections]] held in 1977, the [[Pakistan Military|military]] imposed [[1977 Pakistani coup d'état|martial law]] throughout the land to ease the social unrest in the country. The [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP), [[Communist Party of Pakistan|Communist Party]] of Pakistan (CPP), and other leftist political parties condemned the act.<ref name="The Himal" /> Unofficially, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]] government destroyed the ban on the [[Communist Party of Pakistan|CPP]]; as a result, the presence of communist literature in Pakistan became stronger.<ref name="The Marxist" />
On the other hand, the right-wing groups further consolidated in opposition to the [[Socialism in Pakistan|socialist influence]] in the country. The extremism on both sides grew as did support for a statutory prohibition of such activities in the 1980s.<ref name=Lexington>{{cite book|last=Saha|first=ed. by Santosh C.|title=Religious fundamentalism in the contemporary world : critical social and political issues|year=2004|publisher=Lexington|location=Lanham, Md. [u.a.]|isbn=0739107607|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HeXPlopNwp0C&pg=PA306&lpg=PA306&dq=jam+saqi+case&source=bl&ots=64Dv_rHqW4&sig=2olpK2j-12-Q3W46hrOGODrb838&hl=en&sa=X&ei=U-qOUum6O8_PigLbs4GICA&ved=0CC4Q6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=jam%20saqi%20case&f=true}}</ref> The [[Soviet Union|USSR]]'s [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan|invasion]] of [[Afghanistan]] gave [[President of Pakistan|President]] [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]] an opportunity to legitimatize his regime in the country with the [[United States|Western]] support.
In 1978, the [[Federal Investigation Agency|FIA]] arrested [[Communist Party of Pakistan|communist leader]], [[Jam Saqi]], and raided two houses in [[Karachi]].<ref name="S.K. Shahab Publications">{{cite journal|last=Shaikh|first=Faraz|title=Pakistan Illustrated|year=2005|volume= 15|issue= 7-8|publisher=S.K. Shahab Publications|id=XloTAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> Saqi was booked for a [[trial]] set up by the [[Zia regime|military government]] in 1980 . In addition, the [[Federal Investigation Agency|FIA]] [[Director General of the Federal Investigation Agency|director]] [[Muhammad Azam Qazi|Azam Qazi]] ordered his agents to begin gathering information on the leftist groups uniting under a [[Movement for the Restoration of Democracy|common platform]]; all were [[acquitted]] in the trial by the federal prosecutors. This marked the second case against the [[Communist Party of Pakistan]]; the first was the [[Rawalpindi Conspiracy case]] instituted in the 1950s.
Under this program, a few of the more notable people who were blacklisted or suffered some other persecution are listed here:
*[[Jam Saqi]]— [[Secretary-General]] of the [[Communist Party of Pakistan]] (CPP) *[[Benazir Bhutto]]<ref name="Independent archives">{{cite web|title=Benazir Bhutto appears before a military court in Jam Saqi case in Karachi March 26, 1983|url=http://jamat.pakphotos.net/details.php?image_id=461&mode=search&sessionid=0cf5f926e4caa82c8749f36af7b7b081|work=March 26, 1983|publisher=Independent archives|accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref> — Chairperson of the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] *[[Khan Abdul Wali Khan|Abdul Wali]]— President of [[Awami National Party]] (ANP) *[[Ghaus Bakhsh Bizenjo|Ghaus Bux Bizenjo]]— Intellectual and politician *[[Sohail Sangi]]— Journalist *[[Meraj Muhammad Khan|Mirage M. Khan]]<ref name="Zahid Hussain archives">{{cite web|last=Hussain|first=Zahid|title=Mairaj Mohammad Khan and Police|url=http://w.pakphotos.com/details.php?image_id=9257&mode=search&sessionid=9647c4e3f4c0c20e676b42aa90660370|publisher=Zahid Hussain archives|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> — Communist activist of the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]] *[[Nazeer Abbasi]]— Communist activist of the [[Communist Party of Pakistan|CPP]] *[[Kamal Warsi]]— Journalist
Primarily, the investigations and inquiry focused on the [[Communist Party of Pakistan|Communist Party]]'s [[Secretary-General]], [[Jam Saqi]]. Although, the inquiries were expanded to the [[Socialism in Pakistan|left-wing parties]] of the country, whereas [[Benazir Bhutto]] repeatedly appeared in the [[Judge Advocate General Branch (Pakistan)|military courts]] sessions led by [[Colonel]] Atiq Hussain.<ref name="Saqi Trial to Benazir">{{cite web|title=Saqi Trial to Benazir|url=http://www.pakphotos.com/search.php?search_keywords=1983&sessionid=01eb5ab999a8791feac2f456f7be8e0b|publisher=Photos archives of 1980s|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> She was inquired from 27 March until 29 March 1983, after being cleared by Colonel Atiq.<ref name="PPP USA">{{cite web|last=PPP USA|title=PPP: Socialism to Communism|url=http://www.pppusa.org/chronology.htm|publisher=PPP USA|accessdate=24 November 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028154335/http://www.pppusa.org/chronology.htm|archivedate=28 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At one point, [[Benazir Bhutto]], in the defense of Saqi, declared that "she did not accept the military courts."<ref name="Dawn news archives, 2009"/> She further testified that "Jam Saqi is a patriotic citizen of the state" and demanded his release.<ref name="Dawn news archives, 2009">{{cite news|last=Staff reporter|title=Jam Saqi gets lifetime achievement award|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/944618/jam-saqi-gets-lifetime-achievement-award|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Dawn news archives, 2009|date=May 30, 2009}}</ref> Other accuses were [[Karachi University]]'s professor Jamal Naqvi, Amar Lal, journalists [[Sohail Sangi]], [[Badar Abro]], [[Kamal Warsi]] and Shabbir Shar. Jam Saqi was arrested on 10 December 1978 but was implicated in this case which was lodged about two years later. Naqvi, Abbasi, Warsi and Shar were arrested on 30 July 1980, while Sangi was arrested on 31 July 1980.
==Participants== *'''Defense witnesses:''' Top political leadership including Ms [[Benazir Bhutto]], Mir [[Ghaus Bux Bezinjo]], [[Khan Abdul Wali Khan]], [[Maulana Shah Mohammed Amroti]], [[Mairaj Mohammed Khan]], [[Fatehyab Ali Khan]], among the journalists [[Minhaj Burna]], [[Afzal Siddiqui]], [[Shaikh Ali Mohammed]], [[Shaikh Aziz]], [[Abdullah. J Memon]] then commissioner, Abdul Ghani Dars (Journalist) and others appeared as defense witnesses. *'''Defense Counsels:''' The defense counsels were [[Abdul Wadood]], [[Mohammed Yousuf Leghari]], [[Akhtar Hussain (lawyer)|Akhtar Hussain]], [[Ali Amjad Advocate]] and [[Shafi Mohammedi]].
