[[File:Northwest-territory-usa-1787.png|thumb|right|350px]] The '''Surveyor General of the Northwest Territory''' was a [[United States]] government official responsible for surveying land in the [[Northwest Territory]] in the [[United States]] late in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth century. The position was created in the [[Land Act of 1796]]<ref>{{USStat|1|464}} - Text of Act of May 18, 1796 [[Library of Congress]]</ref> to survey lands ceded by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indians]] northwest of the [[Ohio River]] and above the mouth of the [[Kentucky River]]. This act, and those that followed evolved into the [[Public Land Survey System]].
[[Rufus Putnam]] was appointed to the office in 1797, and held it until 1803. His office was in [[Marietta, Ohio|Marietta]].{{sfn|White|p=218}} In 1801, the position was offered to [[Andrew Ellicott]] by [[Thomas Jefferson]], but he refused, because he was upset at slow pay for work he had done for the Federal Government.{{sfn|Mathews 1908|p=204-206}} [[Jared Mansfield]] held the office from 1803 to 1813. His office was in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]].{{sfn|White|p=218}} [[Josiah Meigs]] held office 1813 to 1815,{{sfn|Williamson 1880|p=170-171}} and [[Edward Tiffin]] from 1815 to his death in 1829.{{sfn|Stewart 1935|p=43}} Tiffin had his office in [[Chillicothe, Ohio|Chillicothe]].{{sfn|White|p=218}} The Surveyor General of Illinois office was created on April 29, 1816, reducing effective area to [[Ohio]], [[Indiana]] and [[Michigan]].{{sfn|White|p=203}} [[Lytle family#William Lytle|William Lytle]] served 1829 until his death in 1831.{{sfn|Howe 1907|p=416}} He moved the office back to Cincinnati.{{sfn|White|p=218}} [[Micajah T. Williams]] held the office 1831 to 1834, when [[Robert Todd Lytle]] took over. [[Ezekiel S. Haines]] was appointed in 1838.{{sfn|Greve 1904|p=673}} [[William Johnston (judge)|Judge William Johnston]] held the office 1841-1845 as thanks for his efforts in supporting the [[United States Whig Party|Whig]] ticket in 1840.{{sfn|Greve 1904|p=771}}{{sfn|Nelson & Runk 1894|p=186-187}}{{sfn|Hunter 1900|p=208-209}} [[Lucius Lyon]] was appointed in 1845, and moved his office to [[Detroit]].{{sfn|White|p=218}} In June, 1845, the Ohio and Indiana offices were closed, and subsequent surveys were made under the [[List of Commissioners of the General Land Office|Commissioner of the General Land Office]].{{sfn|White|p=204, 218}} The Surveyor General was initially paid $2000 per year, and his deputies were paid three dollars per mile surveyed.{{sfn|Stewart 1935|p=37}}
Putnam was occupied in 1797 with laying off the [[Greenville Treaty Line]] and surveying the [[United States Military District]] and [[Moravian Indian Grants]], and he started the survey of [[Congress Lands]] in 1798.{{sfn|Treat 1910|p=93}}
Mansfield is credited with "considerable scientific ability and high standards of workmanship."{{sfn|Stewart 1935|p=38-40}} He laid out astronomically the [[Indiana]] [[Baseline (surveying)|baseline]] and [[Second Principal Meridian]], in spite of the difficulties. Pressures on him are illustrated in a letter [[Secretary of the Treasury]] [[Albert Gallatin]] wrote to Mansfield: "The new act (March 13, 1805) is intended to palliate errors made in surveys north of the Ohio. At four dollars per mile, great correctness cannot be attained in that part of the country. Do your best at that price. Congress desires that corners and boundaries be definitely fixed, and the precise content of each is not equally important. A few acres more or less is not so important as it is that corners and boundaries should be known with precision to avoid litigation. It is of primary importance that the land should be surveyed and subdivided."{{sfn|Stewart 1935|p=38-40}}
Tiffin established the scheme of [[List of principal and guide meridians and base lines of the United States|guide meridians]] and [[standard parallel]]s for townships distant from the principal meridians and baselines, which became a feature of the Public Land Survey System.{{sfn|Stewart 1935|p=44}}
On March 3, 1803,<ref>{{USStat|2|229}} - Text of act of March 3, 1803 (section 10) [[Library of Congress]]</ref> a Surveyor General position was created for lands south of [[Tennessee]], and there followed a number of similar positions over the next years. In 1822, the first surveying district was created, namely the state of [[Ohio]], with an officer called Surveyor-General in charge.{{sfn|Williamson 1880|p=170-171}}
Until the reorganization of the [[General Land Office]] in 1836, each Surveyor General acted more or less independently, setting his own standards for execution of field work.{{sfn|Stewart 1935|p=41}}
